2026-04-16 12:03:49 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Load module protection diode'] hypothesis_explanation='The voltage present at the relay output terminals (11.99V and 0.36V) indicates that voltage is being correctly supplied to the load module input. However, the measurement across the diode in the load module shows only 0.36V at the anode and near 0V at the cathode, and both lamps (main and indicator) receive no measurable voltage (0.0003V). This suggests that the diode is not conducting despite the correct polarity and input voltage, which indicates an open-circuit condition in the diode—most likely a failed (open) diode. This would prevent any current from reaching both lamps, leaving them unpowered even though the rest of the circuit is operating correctly. This fits all observed symptoms, so the most likely fault is a failed (open) load module protection diode.'
